00:00:27.270 --> 00:00:32.049
JULIAN BEINART: The piece that
I've had handed out to you

00:00:32.049 --> 00:00:39.790
covers the trajectory that
we will follow from 1 to 7.

00:00:46.700 --> 00:00:50.420
Let me make a comment
about the formal structure

00:00:50.420 --> 00:00:51.810
of these examples.

00:00:55.490 --> 00:00:59.810
The grid is a
universal language.

00:00:59.810 --> 00:01:05.330
It is used in the cosmic
model in Xi'an in 190 BC.

00:01:05.330 --> 00:01:12.830
And it's used in the 1811
Manhattan extension plan.

00:01:12.830 --> 00:01:18.920
The assumption is, if one
takes this too literally,

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:23.240
is that the grid
is a language which

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:28.695
can perform its function
in almost any context.

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:35.140
That is possibly true.

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:38.380
In each case, it requires
one to ask questions

00:01:38.380 --> 00:01:41.830
about the nature of
the grid-- its context,

00:01:41.830 --> 00:01:49.450
its size, its manifestation,
what the contemporary culture

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:52.690
was attempting to produce.

00:01:52.690 --> 00:01:56.830
The commissioners who laid out
the 1811 Plan for Manhattan

00:01:56.830 --> 00:01:59.620
spoke in terms of
trying to create

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:04.540
the most everyday
environment they could.

00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:06.700
What does every
day mean to them?

00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:09.800
They're the examples
of New Amsterdam,

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:12.730
the Dutch settlement, and
the British settlement,

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:14.680
which followed.

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:18.280
Wall Street, by the
way, was the separation

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:20.590
between the English
and Dutch settlements.

00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:31.800
So the explanation for the
centralized cosmic order

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:36.720
of Xi'an and the
same or similar use

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:41.910
of a grid in
Manhattan many years

00:02:41.910 --> 00:02:54.210
later with this second set
of plans or plans for grids

00:02:54.210 --> 00:03:00.120
of many European center cities.

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:02.970
They're all grids,
but infinitely varied

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:05.220
in size and dimension.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:19.000
The diagram is that of a
Bastide town in the southwest.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.260
This one happens to be a town
which divides the blocks up

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:26.170
according to a
diagonal measurement.

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:31.630
I'll deal with that
move more carefully.

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:35.650
The next is a diagram,
a fictitious diagram,

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:43.000
of a Roman town showing
the rectangularity which

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.330
exists around the
tying of a central knot

00:03:46.330 --> 00:03:49.780
by this subdivision
of the blocks

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:54.070
according to a
horizontal east-west line

00:03:54.070 --> 00:04:01.420
and this north-south line,
the Decumanus and the Cardo.

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:04.630
And the second last--

00:04:04.630 --> 00:04:10.270
the last is an example of
contemporary fascination

00:04:10.270 --> 00:04:17.709
with linearity following the
notion of machine performance.

00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:27.190
Henry Ford who probably
advocated assembly line

00:04:27.190 --> 00:04:32.470
production more than any other
industrialist in modern times

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:38.230
when he wanted to make
his own city in Muscle

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:45.730
Shoals in Alabama, didn't
use a linear system.

00:04:45.730 --> 00:04:49.930
Well, maybe-- there are very
few plans of Muscle Shoals.

00:04:49.930 --> 00:04:55.740
But it was a long city
which really interfaced

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:58.150
agriculture and industry.

00:04:58.150 --> 00:05:02.950
Ford's notion was
that America had

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:05.530
gone wrong in
building industrialism

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:08.874
without agriculture.

00:05:08.874 --> 00:05:11.980
He's postured it for
Muscle Shoals, which I'll

00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:14.110
discuss later in this class.

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:16.690
It's interesting.

00:05:16.690 --> 00:05:22.240
Every person-- Henry Ford
said, anybody who works for me

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:26.530
should spend part of
his time in a garden

00:05:26.530 --> 00:05:32.740
or in a creative agricultural
performance of some kind.

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:41.440
The example on the
second to last page,

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:46.690
Southwest Washington in
plan, and our first notion

00:05:46.690 --> 00:05:52.210
that the city should be made up
over time by points of interest

00:05:52.210 --> 00:05:56.410
based on the topography and
on a diagonalized system

00:05:56.410 --> 00:06:01.240
of connection was
opposed by Jefferson.

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:04.330
Jefferson made an
earlier plan which

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:07.000
is very difficult
to decipher but is

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:12.550
longitudinal and rectangular.

00:06:12.550 --> 00:06:17.060
L'Enfant is quoted here as
saying, how boring a grid plan

00:06:17.060 --> 00:06:17.560
is.

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:30.670
"Grid plans are tiresome and
insipid, however, answerable

00:06:30.670 --> 00:06:33.750
they may appear on
paper or seducing

00:06:33.750 --> 00:06:37.740
as they may be on first
aspect to the eyes,"

00:06:37.740 --> 00:06:40.740
compared to Alexandria
in 77, which

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:43.800
was a rectangular
plan, which was

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:46.080
occupied right
from the beginning

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:53.110
and worked
subsequently very well.

00:06:53.110 --> 00:06:56.520
So one of the aspects
of the machine model,

00:06:56.520 --> 00:07:01.350
which this seems to
suggest, is that it has

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:05.520
a very high speed of return.

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:12.090
You can have a plan in an
extreme situation, which

00:07:12.090 --> 00:07:17.350
requires a minimal
amount of surveying.

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:21.000
It has a high aspect
of legibility.

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:28.380
According to Gestalt's
theorist of urban form,

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:32.250
they would say that it's
because there is only one angle

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:35.010
in a right angle intersection.

00:07:35.010 --> 00:07:38.430
Any other intersection
involves more than one angle.

00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:42.090
And the basic fundamental
law of visual economy,

00:07:42.090 --> 00:07:45.420
would suggest that you
would prefer the security

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:47.190
of the right angle.

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:52.200
That is a linguistic assumption.

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:56.860
And it's probably got a meta
truth associated with it.

00:07:56.860 --> 00:08:02.130
It's not the only reason
that this grid form

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:06.570
appears in the machine model.

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:11.220
The cosmic model, which
we discussed last time,

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:14.010
put forward the ideal
of a crystalline city,

00:08:14.010 --> 00:08:19.050
stable and hierarchical,
a magical microcosmos

00:08:19.050 --> 00:08:24.390
in which each part was fused
into a perfectly ordered whole.

00:08:24.390 --> 00:08:29.190
If it changed at all, it did
so only in this mechanical--

00:08:29.190 --> 00:08:31.860
not in mechanical--
rhythmical, ordered,

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:33.630
completely unchanging way.

00:08:37.120 --> 00:08:40.110
Thinking of the city as a
practical machine on their own

00:08:40.110 --> 00:08:42.999
is an utterly
different conception.

00:08:42.999 --> 00:08:45.450
A machine also has
permanent parts,

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:48.340
but the parts move
and move each other.

00:08:48.340 --> 00:08:50.970
The machine can change,
although it does so

00:08:50.970 --> 00:08:55.430
in some clearly predictable way.

00:08:55.430 --> 00:08:59.010
Stability is inherent in
the parts, not necessarily

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:00.660
in the whole.

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:02.940
A whole grows by addition.

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:07.270
The wider meaning is simply
the sum of its parts.

00:09:07.270 --> 00:09:10.380
It can be taken apart,
put together in reverse.

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:12.690
Its pieces can be replaced.

00:09:12.690 --> 00:09:18.210
It is factual, functional,
cool, not magical at all.

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:26.030
This is a very basic statement,
that you can arm machine

00:09:26.030 --> 00:09:28.820
with magical
properties is perfectly

00:09:28.820 --> 00:09:31.040
possible for the human brain.

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:33.410
We will see in
the later examples

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:43.800
where, in fact, this is an
aspect of the machine model

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:45.900
which appears much later.

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:48.225
In its earliest
times, it's very pure.

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:58.620
The machine model occurs
historically most often

00:09:58.620 --> 00:10:04.140
when its settlements are
temporary, secondly when

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:07.320
they have to be built
in haste or being

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:12.000
built for clear,
limited practical aims.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:17.430
The expansion of Manhattan
North of Houston Street

00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:20.760
invoked no magical properties.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:26.170
When the Rockefellers intervened
and built Rockefeller Center,

00:10:26.170 --> 00:10:32.940
there was some sense they did
so partly, historians claim,

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:37.620
to maintain the hegemony
over that part of Manhattan

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:40.110
where their house was.

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:44.130
Rockefeller Center
can be seen to fit

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:48.030
into the overall machine-like
system of Manhattan,

00:10:48.030 --> 00:10:55.140
yet on its own it evokes
larger cultural invocation.

00:10:55.140 --> 00:11:00.040
We'll talk more about that as
we talk later on in this class

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:03.300
about some of this.

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:18.650
I said, it's most useful
in temporary situations

00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:22.430
when the environment
is built in haste,

00:11:22.430 --> 00:11:26.870
when it's built for clear of
limited practical purposes.

00:11:26.870 --> 00:11:31.610
But it's also used to allocate
land and resources quickly.

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:36.500
There's a kind of built-in idea
of equal distribution in mind

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:38.360
as well.

00:11:38.360 --> 00:11:40.790
You'll recall
Marx's comment which

00:11:40.790 --> 00:11:42.680
I made at the
beginning of the class

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:47.810
about the emerging distinction
between country and city.

00:11:47.810 --> 00:11:50.720
What emerges as
urbanization occurs

00:11:50.720 --> 00:11:54.800
is increasing gap in land
value between anything

00:11:54.800 --> 00:11:58.840
that's urbanized and
anything that ruralized.

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:09.320
To pay back the enormous
investment in labor,

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:11.570
the Romans, for
instance, paid back

00:12:11.570 --> 00:12:15.740
veterans who served
in the army by land.

00:12:15.740 --> 00:12:21.380
It needed to subdivide the
land in an equitable fashion.

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:27.500
The word in English "lot,"
it refers to a plot of land

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:30.410
has the same root
as the word lottery.

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:33.680
The lottery was used
quite extensively

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:36.140
in this equalization.

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:43.460
So the machine model becomes
a checkerboard in some sense

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:52.400
in which you can give people
the promise of land value,

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:57.470
but you cannot exactly
initiate a central point.

00:12:57.470 --> 00:13:00.320
There may be a central point
the crossing of the Cardo

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:04.700
and Decumanus, but that would
be reserved for the Roman Forum,

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:05.930
not for private land.

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:13.340
In the Laws of the
Indies, Los Angeles,

00:13:13.340 --> 00:13:16.550
the last of the Laws of in the
Indies cities in the United

00:13:16.550 --> 00:13:23.480
States, the Central Plaza
was 200 by 400 feet.

00:13:23.480 --> 00:13:25.990
And then the grid
spread out from that.

00:13:29.150 --> 00:13:35.330
So this notion of a democratic
distribution of urban land

00:13:35.330 --> 00:13:40.895
is fundamentally in the process
of urbanizing at low cost--

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:46.590
conditional low cost.

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:50.480
The cosmic model required
enormous investments

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:51.020
in defense.

00:13:56.230 --> 00:14:05.050
The first set of examples we
look at are the Egyptian slave

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:11.590
quarters built to
promote the eternal life

00:14:11.590 --> 00:14:18.280
of the pharaonic
cult. For reasons

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:26.080
which are rather obscure,
Egypt was not accompanied.

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:30.700
Egypt's development
from 3,000 BC onwards

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:35.560
didn't involve
internecine warfare,

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:39.430
which meant that no
investment need to be made

00:14:39.430 --> 00:14:43.240
in wars to defend a local site.

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:46.480
Once you invest
in the local site

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:50.545
and pay for the cost of
fortification, you don't move.

00:14:54.930 --> 00:14:57.660
Cairo was a much
later phenomenon.

00:14:57.660 --> 00:15:04.110
In the 3,000 years
until about 600 BC,

00:15:04.110 --> 00:15:07.680
there were no cities in Egypt.

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:12.420
Thebes and Memphis were
only temporary cities.

00:15:12.420 --> 00:15:19.350
They were built to enable the
construction of the metamorph--

00:15:19.350 --> 00:15:25.860
not metamorphosis-- the
metaphysical structures

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:29.280
for the post-life
of the pharaoh.

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:32.910
It took so much
human labor to build

00:15:32.910 --> 00:15:44.420
one of these cosmic structures
that the idea of labor and cost

00:15:44.420 --> 00:15:48.950
and materials didn't go
into anything which we would

00:15:48.950 --> 00:15:51.200
describe as a normal city.

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:53.480
It went instead
into the business

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:58.310
of construction and the
environment for the afterlife.

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:03.290
Yet that piece of the
pharaonic complex,

00:16:03.290 --> 00:16:08.660
which housed the laborers,
were based on a per striga

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:11.930
system of block
development, which

00:16:11.930 --> 00:16:14.490
we'll show you in the slide.

00:16:14.490 --> 00:16:14.990
But--

00:16:18.210 --> 00:16:19.845
AUDIENCE: I have
a question there.

00:16:19.845 --> 00:16:21.765
JULIAN BEINART: Yes.

00:16:21.765 --> 00:16:23.640
AUDIENCE: If I wanted
to make of these cities

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:27.000
the amount of resources
that you have invested,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:31.020
both in time and
effort, that cements

00:16:31.020 --> 00:16:32.300
the population [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:32.300 --> 00:16:33.720
JULIAN BEINART: Sure, sure.

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:37.180
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE],, how
does it work in cities like--

00:16:37.180 --> 00:16:38.880
I'm thinking of
Teotihuacan in Mexico,

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:43.590
Fatehpur Sikri in India,
that for this vast complex

00:16:43.590 --> 00:16:44.792
that eventually they--

00:16:44.792 --> 00:16:46.500
JULIAN BEINART: Both
of them disappeared.

00:16:49.620 --> 00:16:51.960
Fatehpur Sikri
disappeared because

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:55.920
of a fundamental problem
of water, a miscalculation

00:16:55.920 --> 00:16:58.320
of the amount of
salt in the water,

00:16:58.320 --> 00:16:59.940
which caused the city to be--

00:17:03.200 --> 00:17:06.530
prior to modern times few
cities have disappeared.

00:17:06.530 --> 00:17:09.859
Fatehpur Sikri is one of them.

00:17:09.859 --> 00:17:16.790
Teotihuacan under Mexican rule
became a tourist artifact.

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:20.060
The Aztec religion was
no more fundamental

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:24.589
after the Spanish hegemony.

00:17:24.589 --> 00:17:27.440
So it lost its
fundamental purpose.

00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:31.290
We don't lose citizens
easily anymore.

00:17:31.290 --> 00:17:37.100
And that is an argument will
come about later in this class.

00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:41.780
But bear in it mind,
the death of cities

00:17:41.780 --> 00:17:45.920
is really a phenomenon
of pre-modern times.

00:17:45.920 --> 00:17:50.750
And both examples
you give, in the one

00:17:50.750 --> 00:17:55.820
lost its fundamental
mechanical system.

00:17:55.820 --> 00:18:00.200
Salty water is no longer the
basis for a wonderful town

00:18:00.200 --> 00:18:03.080
that Fatehpur Sikri was.

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:10.160
And Teotihuacan didn't
have an adaptive mechanism

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:13.040
to sustain its growth.

00:18:13.040 --> 00:18:16.460
It was no reason for it to grow.

00:18:16.460 --> 00:18:21.950
Tenochtitlan, on the other
hand, had all of the capacity

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:24.500
as a capital city on the lake.

00:18:24.500 --> 00:18:27.530
The combination of
the mysterious quality

00:18:27.530 --> 00:18:33.890
of the original-- of
the landing of the eagle

00:18:33.890 --> 00:18:35.195
in the center of the cosmos.

00:18:37.700 --> 00:18:42.020
That was taken over as
an astronomic-- anyway,

00:18:42.020 --> 00:18:43.820
we'll talk more about this.

00:18:43.820 --> 00:18:45.290
You raised an
interesting argument.

00:18:50.090 --> 00:18:56.230
According to the fifth century
Greek historian Herodotus

00:18:56.230 --> 00:18:57.410
told--

00:18:57.410 --> 00:19:00.950
I don't know how he knew
this, but 100,000 men

00:19:00.950 --> 00:19:03.410
were engaged for
three months each year

00:19:03.410 --> 00:19:10.670
for 20 years in moving blocks
of stone to a pharaonic site.

00:19:13.710 --> 00:19:15.630
He claims that
there must have been

00:19:15.630 --> 00:19:18.360
something like
4,000 workers which

00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:20.400
had to be housed permanently.

00:19:24.980 --> 00:19:27.740
So Leonard Woolley
the archaeologist

00:19:27.740 --> 00:19:32.750
writing about Tell el-Amarna
describes the housing

00:19:32.750 --> 00:19:37.220
as monotonously alike, each with
its kitchen parlor in front,

00:19:37.220 --> 00:19:39.740
its cupboards and
bedrooms behind,

00:19:39.740 --> 00:19:43.385
the very patina of mechanically
devised industrial building.

00:19:46.070 --> 00:19:49.960
Same arguments made by
other archaeologists.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:57.290
The distinction between
enslavement of labor and cultic

00:19:57.290 --> 00:20:02.881
objectives is characteristic
of this Egyptian phenomenon.

00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:11.540
A more elaborate system
of using the machine model

00:20:11.540 --> 00:20:13.730
takes place in
Hellenistic towns.

00:20:16.700 --> 00:20:19.970
In colonial situations,
it's very unlikely

00:20:19.970 --> 00:20:23.360
that the mother city
will be replicated

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:25.850
in the colonial system.

00:20:25.850 --> 00:20:28.190
Delhi is not like London.

00:20:28.190 --> 00:20:35.000
The Laws of the Indies towns,
Bogota, is not like Madrid.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:39.290
Athens had its own
unique structure.

00:20:39.290 --> 00:20:41.570
It was an Iraqi site.

00:20:41.570 --> 00:20:46.340
It had limited
agricultural resources.

00:20:46.340 --> 00:20:51.830
And it needed to expand as part
of its Mediterranean expansion

00:20:51.830 --> 00:20:56.900
to the south to Africa,
to the east to Asia Minor,

00:20:56.900 --> 00:21:03.065
and to the west eventually to
Sicily and to Southern Italy.

00:21:08.330 --> 00:21:17.240
The building of
colonial empire took

00:21:17.240 --> 00:21:23.060
place not because of the
advantages of the mother city.

00:21:23.060 --> 00:21:26.900
In fact, fifth century
democracy in Athens

00:21:26.900 --> 00:21:29.880
is unlikely to have been spread.

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:34.430
There's one theory that
says the Greek islands

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:38.530
or the Greek colonial sites--

00:21:38.530 --> 00:21:44.180
not islands-- were the result
of the expansion of democracy.

00:21:44.180 --> 00:21:48.740
Democracy only occurred
in the first century BC.

00:21:48.740 --> 00:21:56.420
The colonial expansion
of the Greeks

00:21:56.420 --> 00:22:00.500
prior to that,
the most important

00:22:00.500 --> 00:22:03.590
of the colonial towns,
the grid-like towns,

00:22:03.590 --> 00:22:09.830
was built in 479 by the planner
Hippodamus, who had a stutter,

00:22:09.830 --> 00:22:14.220
he had long hair, and had
interesting political theories.

00:22:14.220 --> 00:22:17.000
He discovered the method
of dividing cities

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.190
and cut up Pireas.

00:22:19.190 --> 00:22:22.850
He's also known
by some historians

00:22:22.850 --> 00:22:25.870
as the inventor of the
gridiron and the father

00:22:25.870 --> 00:22:28.010
of town planning.

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:33.200
Hippodamus, 479, Miletus--
this was the first time

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:40.850
that a town was considered as
a totality in a certain sense.

00:22:40.850 --> 00:22:44.330
All the parts of the
town were in place,

00:22:44.330 --> 00:22:46.070
except perhaps for industry.

00:22:46.070 --> 00:22:48.470
One doesn't know
from archaeology

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:52.190
how much industry took place
in these colonial times.

00:22:52.190 --> 00:22:55.160
They were essentially
trading towns.

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:59.330
Mumford argues that
the grid serves

00:22:59.330 --> 00:23:05.660
as a method for making form of
clarity of international trade.

00:23:08.360 --> 00:23:10.550
There's something to
be said for having

00:23:10.550 --> 00:23:14.630
a recognizable or legible
environment as you

00:23:14.630 --> 00:23:17.780
move into new environments.

00:23:17.780 --> 00:23:19.580
You put your stamp on a place.

00:23:19.580 --> 00:23:23.870
It's almost like building a
Hilton Hotel, which hardly

00:23:23.870 --> 00:23:26.780
serves to emulate
the environment

00:23:26.780 --> 00:23:29.210
or to affect the environment.

00:23:29.210 --> 00:23:33.530
But Mumford's argument is
that modern trade requires

00:23:33.530 --> 00:23:36.680
a standardization of commodity.

00:23:36.680 --> 00:23:41.360
He later on, in talking about
American grid of expediency,

00:23:41.360 --> 00:23:45.710
refers to capitalism and
the grid of expediency

00:23:45.710 --> 00:23:51.960
as phenomenally correct
and absolutely connected.

00:23:51.960 --> 00:23:55.740
Whether this is
true, we will discuss

00:23:55.740 --> 00:23:59.010
as we go through this class.

00:23:59.010 --> 00:24:04.410
There's no absolute connection
between capitalist theory

00:24:04.410 --> 00:24:05.870
and grid phenomena.

00:24:08.750 --> 00:24:15.240
I'll speak to this point
a bit later in this class.

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:18.210
The other towns of
distinction were

00:24:18.210 --> 00:24:21.750
Olynthus in the Northern
Greek peninsula.

00:24:21.750 --> 00:24:23.520
Oh no, it's not on
the peninsula-- it's

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:25.650
further north, north of Athens.

00:24:25.650 --> 00:24:29.250
And Priene, 300 BC.

00:24:29.250 --> 00:24:33.930
All of these involve
the same phenomena

00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.000
shaped within the grid.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:40.080
And agora, a wall, a
wall didn't conform

00:24:40.080 --> 00:24:44.190
to the grid-like system.

00:24:44.190 --> 00:24:47.490
These towns were built
on defensible sites

00:24:47.490 --> 00:24:52.650
so that the wall system was
informal and took account

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:59.990
of the minimum ways of building
infrastructure on sloping land.

00:24:59.990 --> 00:25:04.590
The British architect Peter
Smithson in a talk on the BBC

00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:08.820
once argued against the
classical vocabulary of Greece.

00:25:08.820 --> 00:25:10.710
He of course, is
an architect who

00:25:10.710 --> 00:25:13.740
very interested in informalism.

00:25:13.740 --> 00:25:15.450
And he argued that
one should really

00:25:15.450 --> 00:25:19.530
look at the Greek fortifications
as a structure for one's

00:25:19.530 --> 00:25:25.260
intellectual heritage rather
than the classical system

00:25:25.260 --> 00:25:28.080
of the Greeks.

00:25:28.080 --> 00:25:31.830
Cartilaginous whether he's right
or wrong, and he won't tell us.

00:25:45.580 --> 00:25:52.345
There is no central axis made by
the intersection of major axis.

00:25:52.345 --> 00:25:55.180
The agora was at the center.

00:25:55.180 --> 00:26:00.940
The grid was exemplified, again,
as a grid of absolute equality.

00:26:07.360 --> 00:26:12.040
These towns have had lives
beyond the Greek time.

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:18.130
They were taken by Hellenism,
by Romans, and most of them

00:26:18.130 --> 00:26:19.030
disappeared.

00:26:22.060 --> 00:26:29.470
They couldn't withstand-- the
requirements have changed.

00:26:29.470 --> 00:26:33.970
Greece was replaced as a
power in the Mediterranean

00:26:33.970 --> 00:26:37.540
and [INAUDIBLE] disappeared.

00:26:37.540 --> 00:26:45.540
But I have referred to Mumford.

00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:49.140
He says, I quote, "a new
regularity and system

00:26:49.140 --> 00:26:56.430
in commercial affairs
causes a formal order

00:26:56.430 --> 00:27:01.095
that when you are faced with
the presence of a hill or curved

00:27:01.095 --> 00:27:04.590
bay, there's no
effort to adaptation

00:27:04.590 --> 00:27:08.420
for change of pattern."

00:27:08.420 --> 00:27:14.840
A similar phenomenon
occurs in the Roman Empire.

00:27:14.840 --> 00:27:16.340
I'm just going
through these things

00:27:16.340 --> 00:27:19.730
very quickly because
we're limited in time.

00:27:19.730 --> 00:27:24.140
Each of these examples has
a literature available.

00:27:24.140 --> 00:27:29.900
If any of you want to follow the
particular literature involved,

00:27:29.900 --> 00:27:34.370
just send me an email and
I'll send you the references.

00:27:34.370 --> 00:27:38.330
It's impossible in a class like
this to go into the details

00:27:38.330 --> 00:27:42.050
more than the
general description.

00:27:42.050 --> 00:27:46.460
You have to assume that the
generalizations are correct.

00:27:46.460 --> 00:27:48.860
It's my fault if they wrong.

00:27:55.650 --> 00:27:59.610
Built cities in an empire--

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:07.710
there was no empire to the
extent in the world's history

00:28:07.710 --> 00:28:11.160
prior to the Roman
Empire, not in scale.

00:28:11.160 --> 00:28:16.260
The Romans built something
like 5,627 towns.

00:28:16.260 --> 00:28:18.720
Towns were often
at the intersection

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:21.435
of important points.

00:28:21.435 --> 00:28:29.640
Her empire stretched
from Scotland to Slovakia

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:36.390
to the Middle East
to North Africa.

00:28:36.390 --> 00:28:39.060
Again, some of the same
phenomena occurred.

00:28:39.060 --> 00:28:43.740
Timgad, the great Roman
town in North Africa,

00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:45.990
is a town for veterans.

00:28:45.990 --> 00:28:48.630
It's subdivided
into equal blocks

00:28:48.630 --> 00:28:52.520
to repay veterans for service.

00:28:52.520 --> 00:28:57.450
There are two characteristics
of a Roman town.

00:28:57.450 --> 00:29:00.465
Again, the same phenomenon
of the commercial order,

00:29:00.465 --> 00:29:03.450
of an international
commercial order,

00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:08.420
creating the logic for formal
order or local formal order.

00:29:11.450 --> 00:29:16.650
Germanicus, the
Roman, general says,

00:29:16.650 --> 00:29:19.890
"I can feel I'm
still in Rome if I

00:29:19.890 --> 00:29:24.660
journey from London or the
beginning of London, Londinium,

00:29:24.660 --> 00:29:25.380
to Rome."

00:29:28.830 --> 00:29:34.200
The poet Rutilius Namatianus
says, "a city of the far flung

00:29:34.200 --> 00:29:35.880
Earth you have made."

00:29:35.880 --> 00:29:39.180
So there are two compunctions
in the Roman city.

00:29:39.180 --> 00:29:43.470
The one is to create a locus,
a place of significance,

00:29:43.470 --> 00:29:45.150
much like a camp.

00:29:45.150 --> 00:29:50.460
For that already the
connections to the space outside

00:29:50.460 --> 00:29:53.965
of the town is made by
emphasizing the Cardo

00:29:53.965 --> 00:29:54.840
and Decumanus system.

00:30:00.260 --> 00:30:04.850
We have the Greek town,
much like the magical town

00:30:04.850 --> 00:30:05.360
before it.

00:30:05.360 --> 00:30:08.060
It was an isolated
phenomenon sitting

00:30:08.060 --> 00:30:16.610
on often very complex territory,
and building a wall which

00:30:16.610 --> 00:30:18.780
fitted the territory's form.

00:30:24.470 --> 00:30:29.590
And although there may be a port
here, as in the case of Priene,

00:30:29.590 --> 00:30:34.480
there was no attempt to
connect this to anything else.

00:30:34.480 --> 00:30:36.925
There was no empire
large enough.

00:30:36.925 --> 00:30:48.620
The Roman town was
an empire town.

00:30:51.470 --> 00:30:57.090
The Cardo and Decumanus
centralized in a forum

00:30:57.090 --> 00:31:03.010
and was an version of
an encampment which

00:31:03.010 --> 00:31:05.330
could be built anywhere.

00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:08.560
It's the basis of London,
it's the basis of Paris,

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:11.860
it's the basis of
Bratislava, it's

00:31:11.860 --> 00:31:20.130
the basis of 5,000 settlements.

00:31:20.130 --> 00:31:32.320
That's A. And we call
this castrametation,

00:31:32.320 --> 00:31:35.320
a nominal phenomenon.

00:31:35.320 --> 00:31:40.750
That is to logically extend
the marking of the territory

00:31:40.750 --> 00:31:42.490
outside the town.

00:31:42.490 --> 00:31:44.170
This is called centuriation.

00:31:48.274 --> 00:31:52.060
Sorry, you can't read my
handwriting-- castrametation,

00:31:52.060 --> 00:31:53.680
centuriation.

00:31:53.680 --> 00:32:04.440
That is the measuring of land
outside the town by a surveying

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:11.040
technique using a gromaticus,
a manual on utility

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:17.590
needs how to lay
out parcels of land.

00:32:17.590 --> 00:32:25.080
These were both used for
agricultural purposes

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:29.520
and also as payment for service.

00:32:33.830 --> 00:32:41.600
So the hermetic quality of
the Greek colonial settlement

00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:45.020
is quite different in spirit.

00:32:48.790 --> 00:32:51.955
Every crossing was a town.

00:33:03.710 --> 00:33:10.400
The notion of being
the center of a empire

00:33:10.400 --> 00:33:12.920
is different than the
metaphysics of being

00:33:12.920 --> 00:33:17.180
the center of the Earth.

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:19.760
The one is provable,
the one is not provable.

00:33:19.760 --> 00:33:24.470
The one is metaphysical,
as in the cosmic model.

00:33:24.470 --> 00:33:28.370
You'll remember my
quoting Vassiliadis

00:33:28.370 --> 00:33:37.610
regarding the centeredness
of the archaic world.

00:33:40.280 --> 00:33:46.260
The centeredness
here is the linking.

00:33:46.260 --> 00:33:49.940
Of course, the center of
Rome, with all its fora

00:33:49.940 --> 00:33:57.560
and magnificence, was the
center of a fundamental system

00:33:57.560 --> 00:33:59.980
of financial distribution.

00:33:59.980 --> 00:34:03.350
The Roman Empire was
built on physicality.

00:34:03.350 --> 00:34:09.199
That is, on the learning how
to tax people locally, and then

00:34:09.199 --> 00:34:12.900
feed the money back
into a central place.

00:34:12.900 --> 00:34:17.900
This is the first model
of colonial enterprise.

00:34:17.900 --> 00:34:22.250
You find some wonderful
reactions to it.

00:34:22.250 --> 00:34:27.679
Bellini's opera Norma--
has anybody seen Norma?

00:34:27.679 --> 00:34:29.810
You should see Norma.

00:34:29.810 --> 00:34:32.750
Norma is the story of
the Roman occupation

00:34:32.750 --> 00:34:35.659
of the capital city of Gaul.

00:34:35.659 --> 00:34:42.000
And Norma is the
local woman who leads

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:44.330
the revolt against the Romans.

00:34:44.330 --> 00:34:48.139
She of course falls in love
with a Roman lieutenant.

00:34:48.139 --> 00:34:54.980
And both of them disappear
into the God only knows what.

00:34:59.060 --> 00:35:03.650
Or if you want another
invocation of the Roman city,

00:35:03.650 --> 00:35:08.990
read Shakespeare's
play Coriolanus.

00:35:08.990 --> 00:35:15.860
Coriolanus is a bad Roman
and he suffers on his attempt

00:35:15.860 --> 00:35:20.270
to return to Rome to
his mother center,

00:35:20.270 --> 00:35:25.460
but fails in his attempt.

00:35:25.460 --> 00:35:28.430
OK, there's a lot to be
said about the Romans.

00:35:40.040 --> 00:35:45.710
The territory subdivided by the
gromaticus is generally 6 by 6,

00:35:45.710 --> 00:35:48.050
or 36 units.

00:35:48.050 --> 00:35:50.630
And this is the
circumference of land

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:52.940
plowed by one ox in one day.

00:35:58.560 --> 00:36:02.460
I'm wanting to go through
this very quickly because we

00:36:02.460 --> 00:36:05.880
have to look at some images
and there's no point.

00:36:05.880 --> 00:36:10.170
I'm only trying to make a
central an argument as I

00:36:10.170 --> 00:36:13.080
can about each case.

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:14.970
One of the arguments
I'm not making

00:36:14.970 --> 00:36:19.380
is the influence of materials.

00:36:19.380 --> 00:36:23.640
The Romans were the first
people to invent concrete.

00:36:23.640 --> 00:36:27.420
And the public quality
of the Roman city

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:32.190
is ascribed to the
availability of concrete.

00:36:32.190 --> 00:36:34.090
For those of you
interested, there's

00:36:34.090 --> 00:36:39.450
is a piece by an MIT
Professor, Heather Lechtman

00:36:39.450 --> 00:36:45.210
called Roman Concrete and the
Roman Architecture Revolution.

00:36:45.210 --> 00:36:50.880
She argues that
hydraulic setting cement

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:54.690
was an attractive ceramic
medium for a period buildings.

00:36:54.690 --> 00:36:57.870
These could be processed
at ambient temperatures

00:36:57.870 --> 00:37:00.960
from readily available
raw ingredients

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:03.585
and cast into large,
designated spaces.

00:37:06.420 --> 00:37:09.780
It produced integral
monolithic structures,

00:37:09.780 --> 00:37:13.530
which could be
incrementally extended.

00:37:13.530 --> 00:37:17.880
The Greeks had to meet
in the open space.

00:37:17.880 --> 00:37:20.580
The Jews still meet
in the open space

00:37:20.580 --> 00:37:24.540
up against the Western
Wall against the remnants

00:37:24.540 --> 00:37:27.195
of Herod's Temple.

00:37:27.195 --> 00:37:29.460
The Romans for the
first time made

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:36.370
it possible to enclose
space and convert the spaces

00:37:36.370 --> 00:37:40.410
is no larger than about six
feet enormities corridor

00:37:40.410 --> 00:37:45.120
is a very concrete phenomenon.

00:37:45.120 --> 00:37:48.870
The Pantheon is an example.

00:37:48.870 --> 00:37:51.660
But Lechtman doesn't only
refer to the Pantheon.

00:37:51.660 --> 00:37:55.500
She refers to the aqueducts,
to the whole system

00:37:55.500 --> 00:37:59.160
of building public buildings
at the scale that they did.

00:37:59.160 --> 00:38:01.365
The Greeks weren't
great builders.

00:38:01.365 --> 00:38:02.675
They were aesthetes.

00:38:07.440 --> 00:38:12.440
There's a thesis last year by
Daniele Cappelletti who argues

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:16.340
that the Romans enabled the
beginning of what he called

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:18.410
[INAUDIBLE] architecture--

00:38:18.410 --> 00:38:20.720
that is, the interior
of buildings.

00:38:20.720 --> 00:38:23.360
The Greeks weren't
interested in interiors--

00:38:23.360 --> 00:38:27.986
they were exterior,
externalizers.

00:38:27.986 --> 00:38:31.750
A plan of the agora
doesn't follow any access.

00:38:31.750 --> 00:38:37.010
It's a jumble of things,
much like the Mayan town.

00:38:37.010 --> 00:38:41.330
If you devote yourself to
creating buildings which only

00:38:41.330 --> 00:38:44.780
makes sense given the
exterior, what they can see

00:38:44.780 --> 00:38:54.080
or how they can be seen, you
can deviate from the model

00:38:54.080 --> 00:38:55.595
that the Romans used.

00:38:58.910 --> 00:39:02.630
The post-Roman period,
we call the Middle Ages.

00:39:06.110 --> 00:39:09.620
In my learning of history,
these were the Dark Ages.

00:39:09.620 --> 00:39:12.050
Nothing happened--
the world only

00:39:12.050 --> 00:39:19.070
emerged after a period of
immense turmoil in Europe.

00:39:21.620 --> 00:39:28.070
There's been recent history done
on this period from 300 to 900

00:39:28.070 --> 00:39:35.495
AD, from 400 to 880 AD,
to mention two new books.

00:39:39.980 --> 00:39:44.170
There's not too much to be said.

00:39:44.170 --> 00:39:51.600
The Roman system was
localized in every respect.

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:55.230
Large families and the
church took over sites

00:39:55.230 --> 00:39:59.940
from Roman camps.

00:39:59.940 --> 00:40:06.720
The fiscal system-- there wasn't
a centralized economy funding

00:40:06.720 --> 00:40:11.400
taxation into Rome,
so each set up

00:40:11.400 --> 00:40:14.130
a competitive system for towns.

00:40:16.710 --> 00:40:19.620
One of the things that
the Roman roads did

00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:26.710
was to allow the subsequent
cultures to use the system

00:40:26.710 --> 00:40:31.650
of moving large distances.

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:35.760
The Christian Church
took advantage of this.

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:46.260
In the story of [INAUDIBLE]
what's the town in the--

00:40:52.740 --> 00:40:55.230
my mind has slipped--

00:40:55.230 --> 00:40:57.720
the town I wrote about
in the first reading?

00:41:02.210 --> 00:41:06.200
It's [INAUDIBLE] one of the
saintly cities in Northern

00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:09.867
Spain, [INAUDIBLE] named--

00:41:09.867 --> 00:41:10.700
AUDIENCE: Compostela

00:41:10.700 --> 00:41:12.080
JULIAN BEINART: Compostela.

00:41:12.080 --> 00:41:13.970
Of course, it's
named after James.

00:41:13.970 --> 00:41:19.220
It's got the same name as San
Diego and all of the-- sorry,

00:41:19.220 --> 00:41:22.460
I try to remember too much.

00:41:26.450 --> 00:41:31.490
Pilgrimage was made possible
by virtue of the Roman roads,

00:41:31.490 --> 00:41:36.920
so was in medieval
connections in commerce.

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:44.210
A pilgrim could come to
Compostela from Bulgaria,

00:41:44.210 --> 00:41:51.320
walk or take a donkey,
move through France

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:54.650
where they would stay
in religious hostels,

00:41:54.650 --> 00:41:58.040
eat Coquilles
Saint-Jacques, which

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:04.760
is the food which emanates from
Compostela, because Compostela

00:42:04.760 --> 00:42:12.050
is a signature in the scallop,
much like shell petroleum.

00:42:12.050 --> 00:42:17.135
It adopted the scallop
as its important logo.

00:42:20.210 --> 00:42:26.360
I think the first
post-medieval notion

00:42:26.360 --> 00:42:31.580
of the machine-like
phenomenon occurs

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:36.890
with the expansion
in the 13th century

00:42:36.890 --> 00:42:40.640
of the French Bastide towns.

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:53.510
Bastides is B-A-S-T-I-D-E-S.
In the 13th century,

00:42:53.510 --> 00:43:01.210
